Part 2 – Adaptor trimming comparison

  1. Look into the adaptor trimming options for cutadapt, process_shortreads, and Trimmomatic (all on Talapas), and briefly describe the differences. Pick one of these to properly trim adapter sequences. Use default settings. What proportion of reads (both forward and reverse) was trimmed?

Differences

  • cutadapt:
    • Takes only a single file
    • Can only do 3’ or 5’ adapters, not both, in a single command
    • Barcode is declared as a flag in the command
  • process_shortreads:
    • Can take both the forward and reverse reads simultaneously
    • Has quality filtering for dropping reads with uncalled bases or low quality scores
    • Requires a list of barcodes
  • Trimmomatic:
    • Can take both the forward and reverse reads simultaneously
    • Has options for numerous quality filters and trimming settings
    • Requires a FASTA file containing your adapters with certain flags dictating how they should be used

Trimmomatic

  • To run Trimmomatic, I had to make the FASTA file, which I named indices.fasta and contined the following information:

    >index1
ACGATCAG
>index2
CTGATCGT
  • I submitted the trimmomatic.srun slurm script to run Trimmomatic on both libraries, one after the other
  • I used the example ILLUMINACLIP:<fastaWithAdaptersEtc>:2:30:10 settings:
    • Maximum of 2 mismatches in the adapter to occur, which will still allow a full match
    • 30 specifies how accurate the match between the two ‘adapter ligated’ reads must be for PE palindrome read alignment (from documentation)
      • I did not include palindrome trimming flags in my FASTA file, so this is unnecessary other than a placeholder
    • 10 specifies how accurate the match between any adapter etc. sequence must be against a read (from documentation)
